    id: 118,
    tags: ["Indian History & Culture"],
    title: "Emperor Ashoka: the warrior-king who chose peace",
    category: "Indian History & Culture",
    emoji: "☸️",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1598619585417-5259ae726f06?w=800&q=80",
    readTime: 6,
    body: `In 261 BCE, Ashoka, emperor of the Maurya dynasty and ruler of the largest empire the Indian subcontinent had ever seen, won the Battle of Kalinga. The victory was total. Around 100,000 people were killed in battle; another 150,000 were deported; perhaps 200,000 more died from the conflict's consequences. Ashoka surveyed the devastation he had caused and experienced what he later described as a profound moral reckoning. "When an independent country is conquered," he wrote on a rock edict that survives today, "the slaughter, death and deportation of the people is extremely grievous to the Beloved of the Gods and weighs heavily on his mind." It was among the most remarkable reversals in the history of power: a conqueror at the height of his strength choosing to renounce conquest.\n\nAshoka converted to Buddhism after Kalinga and spent the remaining three decades of his reign promoting what he called Dhamma — a social and ethical code emphasising non-violence, religious tolerance, compassion for humans and animals, and proper conduct. He was not a passive moralist. He backed his principles with action. He issued edicts — inscribed on rocks and stone pillars across his empire, stretching from Afghanistan to the tip of India — that remain the earliest surviving substantial inscriptions in the Indian subcontinent. He established hospitals and veterinary clinics, planted trees and dug wells along roads, and appointed Dhamma officials to oversee the welfare of both people and animals.\n\nHis edicts explicitly required respect for all religious sects: "Beloved of the Gods wishes that all religions should reside everywhere, for all of them desire self-control and purity of heart." This was not tolerance as a grudging concession; it was a positive principle that the diversity of belief was worthy of respect. In an age when rulers typically imposed religious conformity, this stance was extraordinary.\n\nAshoka's empire — the Mauryan Empire — was the first to unite almost the entire Indian subcontinent under a single administration. His grandfather Chandragupta Maurya had founded it; his father Bindusara had expanded it; Ashoka completed the task with the conquest of Kalinga and then refused to conquer further. The Mauryan state maintained a sophisticated bureaucracy, standardised weights and measures, a postal system, and trade networks that reached the Mediterranean. Ashoka dispatched Buddhist missionaries to Sri Lanka, Southeast Asia, Central Asia, and the Hellenistic kingdoms of the Middle East — a mission that would make Buddhism the dominant religion of Asia.\n\nAshoka is largely absent from Indian nationalist memory until the 20th century, when B.R. Ambedkar and others recovered him as a symbol of an alternative, non-Brahminical strand of Indian civilisation. Independent India adopted Ashoka's lion capital as its national emblem and placed his Dharma Chakra — the wheel of law — at the centre of the national flag. These choices are not coincidental: they represent a conscious claim about what kind of civilisational inheritance India wishes to claim.`,
    quiz: {
      type: "mcq",
      questions: [
        { q: "What event transformed Ashoka's worldview and led him to embrace Buddhism?", opts: ["A meeting with the Buddha's descendants", "The death of his father", "The devastating Battle of Kalinga", "A dream sent by the gods"], ans: 2 },
        { q: "What was Ashoka's concept of Dhamma?", opts: ["A military code for his army", "An ethical code of non-violence, tolerance and compassion", "A set of Hindu religious laws", "A system of taxation"], ans: 1 },
        { q: "Where does India use Ashoka's symbol today?", opts: ["On currency only", "On the national flag and national emblem", "On all government buildings", "In Buddhist temples"], ans: 1 },
      ]
    }
