    id: 120,
    tags: ["Indian History & Culture"],
    title: "The British Raj: how India was colonised — and what it cost",
    category: "Indian History & Culture",
    emoji: "⚖️",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1558618666-fcd25c85cd64?w=800&q=80",
    readTime: 6,
    body: `In 1750, India accounted for roughly 25% of global manufacturing output. By 1900, after a century and a half of British rule, that share had fallen to 2%. The British Raj — the period of direct British Crown rule over India from 1858 to 1947, preceded by the East India Company's commercial and military conquest from the 1750s onwards — is one of history's most consequential colonial projects, and understanding it is essential to understanding both modern India and the world that colonialism made.\n\nThe East India Company began as a trading enterprise, obtaining its first foothold in India through the Mughal emperor Jahangir's grant of trading rights in 1612. For over a century it operated primarily as a commercial venture. The transformation to political and military power was gradual and opportunistic. The Battle of Plassey in 1757, in which Company forces under Robert Clive defeated the Nawab of Bengal partly through bribery of the Nawab's own general, gave the Company effective control of Bengal — the wealthiest province of India. From Bengal, the Company extended its power through a combination of military conquest, alliance, and manipulation of succession disputes, until by the 1840s it controlled virtually the entire subcontinent.\n\nThe economic consequences of colonial rule have been extensively studied by economist Utsa Patnaik, who estimates that Britain extracted roughly $45 trillion from India between 1765 and 1938, using a mechanism she calls the "drain of wealth": Indian tax revenues were used to purchase Indian goods for export to Britain, meaning India was effectively paying for its own exploitation. Indian textile industries, which had produced the finest cotton cloth in the world and dominated global trade, were destroyed by British manufacturing imports backed by tariff policies that protected British goods while flooding Indian markets.\n\nThe Raj also brought consequences that Indians in different political traditions evaluate differently: railways (built to move goods to ports, not to connect Indian communities), an English-language education system (which produced an Indian elite alienated from indigenous traditions but equipped with the conceptual tools that would eventually run an independent democracy), census operations that hardened fluid religious identities into fixed categories, and the codification of "personal law" that entrenched religious community as the basis of legal identity.\n\nThe 1943 Bengal famine killed between 2 and 3 million people — largely the result of British wartime policies that diverted food from Bengal to sustain the war effort and refused international offers of food aid. Winston Churchill's response — suggesting that Indians brought it on themselves by "breeding like rabbits" — encapsulates an imperial attitude toward Indian life that made the Raj's end inevitable once it became politically imaginable. The independence movement, led by Gandhi's strategy of non-violent resistance, eventually made the cost of maintaining the Raj — in international legitimacy, Indian resistance, and simple exhaustion after World War II — too high to bear. Britain left in 1947, partitioning the subcontinent in a division that produced one of the largest mass migrations in human history and the deaths of perhaps a million people in sectarian violence.`,
    quiz: {
      type: "mcq",
      questions: [
        { q: "What event marked the beginning of East India Company political power in India?", opts: ["The arrival of Vasco da Gama in 1498", "The Battle of Plassey in 1757", "The Sepoy Mutiny of 1857", "The grant of trading rights in 1612"], ans: 1 },
        { q: "What does economist Utsa Patnaik argue about the 'drain of wealth'?", opts: ["India lost wealth through poor internal governance", "Britain extracted roughly $45 trillion from India between 1765 and 1938", "The Raj invested more in India than it took", "India's wealth declined due to the Mughal collapse"], ans: 1 },
        { q: "What caused the 1943 Bengal famine?", opts: ["A drought affecting all of India", "British wartime policies diverting food from Bengal", "A failure of the monsoon for multiple years", "A plague that wiped out crops"], ans: 1 },
      ]
    }
