    id: 123,
    tags: ["Indian History & Culture"],
    title: "Bollywood: how India built the world's largest film industry",
    category: "Indian History & Culture",
    emoji: "🎬",
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1524492412937-b28074a5d7da?w=800&q=80",
    readTime: 5,
    body: `Every year, Indian cinema produces more films than any other country on Earth — roughly 1,800 films annually, in more than 20 languages, watched by approximately 1.4 billion admissions. "Bollywood" — the Hindi-language film industry based in Mumbai, formerly called Bombay — is the most globally recognised of these industries, but it is only one strand of a rich tapestry that includes Tamil cinema (Kollywood), Telugu cinema (Tollywood), Malayalam cinema, Bengali cinema, and many more.\n\nIndian cinema began in 1913 when Dadasaheb Phalke, a photographer and printer inspired by a visit to see a film about the life of Jesus Christ, resolved to create an Indian mythological film. He spent three months studying the technology in London, bought a camera and equipment, and began shooting Raja Harishchandra — a story from the Mahabharata — in his Bombay home. Phalke's wife played one of the lead roles, as Indian women at the time refused to appear in films. Released in May 1913, it ran for three weeks to packed audiences.\n\nHindi cinema developed its distinctive formula over the following decades: songs and dances woven into narratives that often drew on mythological and folk storytelling traditions, spectacular emotional performances, moral conflicts resolved through a combination of love, sacrifice, and justice, and a duration of three hours that European cinema had long since abandoned. The formula was not a failure of sophistication — it reflected an audience tradition of participatory, festival-like entertainment very different from the quiet, passive European cinema-going experience. Indian audiences sang along, talked back to the screen, and threw coins at the image of beloved stars.\n\nThe golden age of Hindi cinema in the 1940s-60s produced works of genuine artistic ambition: Guru Dutt's Pyaasa (1957) and Kaagaz Ke Phool (1959), both meditations on artistic failure and commercial compromise; Mehboob Khan's Mother India (1957), which lost the Academy Award for Best Foreign Film by a single vote; Bimal Roy's neorealist dramas influenced by Italian cinema. These directors worked within the commercial system but pushed against its constraints.\n\nThe New Wave of the 1970s brought angry young men — most famously Amitabh Bachchan, who became the biggest star in the world during a decade of social anxiety — and with them a harder, more urban cinema that replaced the rural arcadias of earlier films with city streets and underworld gangsters. By the 1990s, the diaspora had emerged as a major audience, and films like Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge (1995) — which ran for 25 years straight in one Mumbai cinema — created a new template of NRI romance.\n\nToday, Indian cinema is in unprecedented international expansion. RRR (2022) won an Oscar for Best Original Song. The Malayalam film industry, producing artistically ambitious low-budget films with strong stories, has attracted global streaming audiences. South Korean success in global cinema has been watched carefully in India as a model for what committed artistic ambition can achieve. The world is discovering what India has known for a century: that Indian cinema is not a lesser version of Hollywood but a distinct artistic tradition with its own logic, pleasures, and power.`,
    quiz: {
      type: "mcq",
      questions: [
        { q: "Who made India's first feature film, Raja Harishchandra?", opts: ["Raj Kapoor", "Dadasaheb Phalke", "Guru Dutt", "Mehboob Khan"], ans: 1 },
        { q: "Which film ran for 25 years straight in one Mumbai cinema?", opts: ["Mother India", "Sholay", "Mughal-E-Azam", "Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge"], ans: 3 },
        { q: "Which Indian film won an Oscar for Best Original Song in 2022?", opts: ["Baahubali", "KGF", "RRR", "Pushpa"], ans: 2 },
      ]
    }
