    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506126613408-eca07ce68773?w=800&q=80",
    readTime: 5,
    body: `Three hundred million people worldwide practise some form of yoga. It is taught in school gyms, hospital rehabilitation programmes, corporate wellness days, and luxury retreats from Bali to Beverly Hills. A $130 billion global industry has grown around it. And most practitioners know almost nothing about what yoga actually is — a 3,000-year-old Indian philosophical system concerned not primarily with physical flexibility but with the liberation of consciousness from the cycles of suffering and rebirth.\n\nThe word "yoga" comes from the Sanskrit root "yuj," meaning to yoke or unite — the same root as the English word "yoke." The unity in question is between the individual self (atman) and the universal consciousness (Brahman), between the limited personal ego and the infinite ground of being. Yoga in its classical sense is a path — one of several described in the Bhagavad Gita — toward moksha, liberation from the cycle of death and rebirth. The physical postures (asana) that Western yoga has elevated to its central practice were, in the classical tradition, considered merely one of eight "limbs" of yoga, and a relatively minor one at that.\n\nThe Yoga Sutras of Patanjali, compiled around 400 CE, describe the eight limbs (ashtanga): ethical restraints (yama), personal disciplines (niyama), physical postures (asana), breath control (pranayama), withdrawal of the senses (pratyahara), concentration (dharana), meditation (dhyana), and ultimate absorption (samadhi). The goal of asana practice in this framework was to prepare the body to sit comfortably in meditation for extended periods — nothing more. The elaborate gymnastic system of postures taught in modern yoga studios has its origins not in ancient tradition but in a 20th-century synthesis.\n\nModern postural yoga was largely created by T. Krishnamacharya, a yoga teacher who worked in Mysore in the 1930s under the patronage of the Maharaja of Mysore. Krishnamacharya synthesised ancient yoga texts with Swedish gymnastics, Indian wrestling exercises, and his own innovations to create a dynamic physical system. His students — most famously B.K.S. Iyengar, K. Pattabhi Jois, and Indra Devi — carried these teachings to the West, where they were adapted further, and some elements — the spiritual framework, the Sanskrit terminology, the philosophical depth — were gradually stripped away.\n\nThis history raises complex questions about cultural appropriation, authenticity, and the globalisation of spiritual practices. Indian scholars and practitioners have been divided. Some welcome yoga's global spread as a form of cultural soft power; others object to the commercialisation of a sacred tradition and the erasure of its Hindu origins. The Indian government's declaration of an International Day of Yoga (21 June, adopted by the United Nations in 2015) reflects an official effort to reassert Indian ownership of a tradition that Western commerce has substantially colonised. The deeper practice — the ethical commitments, the meditative depth, the philosophical framework — remains available to anyone willing to look past the mat.`,
