    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1532375810709-75b1da00537c?w=800&q=80",
    readTime: 6,
    body: `On 15 August 1947, Jawaharlal Nehru spoke to a newly independent India in words that have echoed through history: "Long years ago we made a tryst with destiny, and now the time comes when we shall redeem our pledge." It was the culmination of a struggle that had consumed generations, deployed extraordinary moral courage, shaped the 20th century's understanding of colonial resistance, and produced, at its moment of triumph, a tragedy of partition that would haunt the new nation for decades.\n\nThe Indian independence movement was not a single movement but a coalition of forces, philosophies, and strategies that sometimes worked together and sometimes pulled apart. The Indian National Congress, founded in 1885 by both Indian and British liberals as a forum for educated Indian political participation, gradually became the primary vehicle of nationalist politics. Its early leaders — Bal Gangadhar Tilak, Gopal Krishna Gokhale, Bipin Chandra Pal — debated whether to work within or against the colonial system. Tilak, who famously declared "Swaraj is my birthright and I shall have it," represented the more confrontational tradition.\n\nGandhi's entry into Indian politics after 1920 transformed the movement. His strategy of mass non-violent civil disobedience brought millions of ordinary Indians — not just the educated elite — into active participation. The Non-Cooperation Movement of 1920-22, the Civil Disobedience Movement launched with the Salt March in 1930, and the Quit India Movement of 1942 each mobilised unprecedented numbers of people willing to court arrest, beatings, and worse. The Quit India Movement, launched as World War II raged, was the most radical: Gandhi called for the British to leave immediately, and when he and other Congress leaders were arrested, a massive spontaneous uprising followed — the largest against British rule since 1857.\n\nThe independence movement encompassed more than Congress and Gandhi. Subhas Chandra Bose, who rejected non-violence as inadequate, escaped British custody and reached Germany, then Japan, to raise the Indian National Army from Indian prisoners of war to fight the British in Southeast Asia. The INA's military efforts largely failed, but the trials of its officers in 1945 became a public relations disaster for the British — Indian public opinion rallied behind the INA soldiers, and the Indian armed forces showed signs of disloyalty to the Crown. B.R. Ambedkar led the struggle for the rights of Dalits (formerly called "untouchables"), insisting that Indian independence must mean freedom for those oppressed within Indian society as well as from British rule.\n\nThe British decision to leave was driven by exhaustion — Britain was bankrupted by World War II — but also by the growing costs of maintaining the Raj in the face of organised resistance, international pressure in the new United Nations era, and the instability demonstrated by the Royal Indian Navy Mutiny of 1946. Lord Mountbatten, appointed as the last Viceroy, accelerated the timetable for independence to August 1947, with catastrophic consequences for the management of partition. Independence came, as Nehru had said, at midnight — and with it, in the same moment, the beginning of Pakistan and the beginning of the communal violence that would kill hundreds of thousands. The tryst with destiny was kept, but its terms were more terrible than anyone had wished.`,
